      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Home Staging for Brisbane Sellers
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Practical presentation that improves your sale result. What to spend, what to skip, and what Brisbane buyers are actually looking for when they walk through the door.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Staging is one of those words that can mean anything from a full furniture rental package worth several thousand dollars to simply removing half the furniture from a lounge room. The version that matters for most Brisbane sellers is somewhere in between: a focused, deliberate effort to help buyers picture themselves living in the property, starting at the moment they see the listing photos and continuing through the first open home. The goal is not decoration. It is emotional connection, and it has a measurable effect on price and days on market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What staging is and what it is not</h2>
      <p>Staging is presentation for sale, not renovation. It does not mean spending $50,000 on a new kitchen or replastering the facade. It means removing what distracts, cleaning what is dirty, fixing what buyers will use to discount their offer, and presenting the space so it photographs well and feels welcoming at inspection. The confusion between staging and renovation is one of the most expensive mistakes sellers make: spending $30,000 on work that adds $10,000 to the sale price while leaving the easier, cheaper items undone.</p>

      <p>The evidence for what staging does to price is consistent. Properties that are presented well sell faster and attract stronger offers than comparable properties that are not. The gap is particularly pronounced in Brisbane's competitive inner east, where buyers are attending multiple inspections each weekend and making fast comparative judgements. A property that presents as cared for and move-in ready gives buyers confidence. A property with dirty carpets, scuffed walls, and a cluttered garage introduces doubt, and doubt shows up in offer prices.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The priorities in order of return</h2>
      <p>If your preparation budget is limited, the following order reflects where you will get the most return for your spend in Brisbane's market. These are not opinions. They are based on what actually affects buyer perception and offer price consistently across comparable sales.</p>

      <p><strong>1. Declutter.</strong> Remove approximately 30% of the furniture and personal items from every room. The instinct is to show the property fully furnished because it looks lived in. The effect, especially on camera, is that rooms look small and buyers focus on the stuff rather than the space. Pack it into a storage unit before photography. Buyers buy the space; let them see it.</p>

      <p><strong>2. Deep clean.</strong> This is not a standard clean. It is grout lines, the inside of the oven, the area behind the toilet, windows front and back, ceiling fans, light fittings, and the inside of kitchen cupboards if any are likely to be opened at inspection. Buyers notice smell before anything else when they walk through a door. A house that smells clean, neutral, and fresh starts the inspection on the right note. One that does not has already planted a negative impression that photographs and styling cannot fix.</p>

      <p><strong>3. Maintenance items.</strong> Walk through the property with a fresh eye and list every item a buyer would notice: dripping taps, stiff doors, cracked tiles, broken fly screens, marks on walls, a gate that does not close properly, missing light covers, a pool that is green. Buyers use visible maintenance deferred to estimate what is hidden, and they almost always over-estimate. A $200 plumber visit and $150 in hardware supplies can neutralise $15,000 worth of offer discounting.</p>

      <p><strong>4. Paint.</strong> Fresh neutral paint on tired walls is high return. You do not need to repaint the whole house. Focus on the rooms that need it most: the main bedroom, the living areas visible from the entrance, and any room with personalised colour choices that will not appeal broadly. A clean white or soft warm neutral works well with Brisbane's light and photographs reliably.</p>

      <p><strong>5. Garden and entry.</strong> The entry and front garden create the first impression for every buyer who arrives at an open home, and they set the emotional tone for everything that follows. Mow, edge, mulch, and remove dead plants. Pressure wash the driveway if it is stained. Replace a tired door mat. Make sure the house number is clearly visible. These are low-cost items that have outsized effect on first impression.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Professional photography is not optional</h2>
      <p>In 2027, more than 90% of buyers begin their property search online. They are scrolling through listing photos at speed, and a property with poor photography does not make it to the shortlist for inspection. It is that simple. Professional photography is not a nice-to-have. It is the primary marketing asset your campaign runs on, and spending $600 to $900 on a skilled real estate photographer is among the highest-returning investments available to any seller.</p>

      <p>Twilight photography has particular value for properties with strong outdoor areas or good street presence. The warm light of a Brisbane evening, combined with interior lights on and the outdoor area lit, creates images that stand out in a listing feed of daytime photographs. For properties where the lifestyle element is a genuine selling point, it is worth the additional cost.</p>

      <p>Drone photography is worth considering for properties with strong aspect, significant land area, or an elevated position. For a standard 600 square metre lot in a flat inner-east suburb, it adds less than the cost implies. Your agent should advise you on whether the property warrants it based on what the aerial angle actually shows.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to hire a professional stylist</h2>
      <p>A professional property stylist, distinct from a photographer, manages the physical presentation of the property: furniture arrangement, art, soft furnishings, plants, and in some cases a full furniture package for vacant properties. The decision of whether to hire one depends on three factors: whether the property is vacant, the price bracket, and whether the existing furniture suits the style and scale of the home.</p>

      <p>Vacant properties almost always benefit from professional styling. An empty house photographs poorly, feels echoey and cold at inspection, and gives buyers no reference for how rooms function or what they can hold. A furniture package transforms the experience. The cost is typically $2,000 to $5,000 for a standard inner-Brisbane home for a four to six week campaign period, and it consistently delivers more than it costs in a competitive market.</p>

      <p>For occupied properties, the question is whether your existing furniture serves the presentation or works against it. A skilled stylist can often work with what you have, supplementing with key hero pieces rather than replacing everything. A brief consultation with a stylist before you decide is usually worthwhile. Most will give you an honest assessment of whether a full package or targeted additions will produce the best result for your property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to spend money on before selling</h2>
      <p>The items sellers most commonly over-invest in before selling are major renovations. A new kitchen in a house where everything else is original and unrenovated does not produce a proportionate return. Buyers immediately notice the contrast and discount accordingly. Structural work that addresses a legitimate defect (a leaking roof, a subsiding stump, a failed retaining wall) is different from cosmetic renovation and is worth fixing because it affects marketability and pricing. But a bathroom retile, new cabinetry, or a deck extension that you personally want will rarely return its cost at sale.</p>

      <p>Highly personalised improvements also reduce buyer appeal rather than increase it. A theatre room conversion, a landscaped tropical garden with a custom water feature, or a very specific built-in storage system may be exactly what you wanted. They will not be what most buyers want, and they narrow the buyer pool rather than widening it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Brisbane-specific presentation: what local buyers pay attention to</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's inner-east market has specific presentation priorities that differ from cooler southern cities. Buyers here are buying a lifestyle as much as a building, and the outdoor areas matter in a way that is hard to overstate.</p>

      <p><strong>Indoor-outdoor flow.</strong> A covered outdoor entertaining area that connects well to the living zone is a primary selling feature for family buyers. If the connection between inside and outside is disrupted by clutter, poor furniture choice, or an outdoor area that looks uncared for, you lose the feature that justifies a significant portion of the price. Stage the outdoor entertaining area with the same attention you give the lounge room.</p>

      <p><strong>Light and airflow.</strong> Queensland buyers understand humidity and expect homes to manage it. Ceiling fans in good working order, windows that open properly, and good cross-ventilation are functional values in this market, not aesthetic ones. Open the house up fully for photography and inspections. Draw back every curtain and blind. Turn on ceiling fans. Let the home demonstrate what it does well in Brisbane's climate.</p>

      <p><strong>Pool presentation.</strong> If the property has a pool, it needs to be clean, balanced, and visually clear for photography and every open home. A green or cloudy pool damages buyer perception far out of proportion to what it costs to fix. Budget for regular treatment in the weeks before the campaign launches and through the campaign itself. If the pool has cosmetic issues such as staining or dated coping, discuss with your agent whether addressing them before sale is worth the investment at your price point.</p>

      <p><strong>Pets.</strong> Remove evidence of pets for photography and inspections. This means pet beds, bowls, toys, any damage to gardens or fences, and odour. Buyers who are not pet owners are often the strongest buyers in the inner east, and a home that signals heavy pet occupation narrows the pool. This is not a permanent change; it is a campaign management decision.</p>

